      <data key="d0">STATIONARY TESTS WITH MANNEQUINS — EMISSION AT RIGHT REARMOST PART OF BUS</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">Mannequin-based stationary tests where CO2 was emitted from the right rearmost part of the bus, and inhalation (P_CO2) was measured at passenger positions. Some missing points were replaced by averages of surrounding data.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.62</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="STATIONARY TESTS WITH MANNEQUINS — EMISSION AT FRONT CENTER (STANDING)">
      <data key="d0">STATIONARY TESTS WITH MANNEQUINS — EMISSION AT FRONT CENTER (STANDING)</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">Mannequin-based stationary tests where CO2 was emitted from the front center (standing) position, and inhalation (P_CO2) was measured at passenger positions. Missing data for one point was replaced by the average of surrounding data.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.62</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_4</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WINDOWS OPEN">
      <data key="d0">WINDOWS OPEN</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Opening bus windows to enable natural ventilation and dilution of rebreathed air and aerosols; explicitly tested as the condition 'windows open, AC off, fan off' in the stationary city bus exposure comparisons.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.9</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="WINDOWS CLOSED, AC OFF, FAN OFF">
      <data key="d0">WINDOWS CLOSED, AC OFF, FAN OFF</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">A sealed baseline configuration in the stationary bus: windows closed, air conditioning off, and auxiliary fans off; used as a reference condition in normalized exposure comparisons.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AC ON">
      <data key="d0">AC ON</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Operation of the bus air conditioning system in the 'on' state, altering airflow patterns and mixing; evaluated in the study of relationships between normalized CO2 and particle exposure at multiple positions.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="AC OFF">
      <data key="d0">AC OFF</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Air conditioning in the 'off' state, used as a comparative condition to assess how the absence of AC-driven airflow affects the coupling between CO2 and particle exposure in the bus.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAN SUPPLY (FRONT) &amp; EXHAUST (REAR)">
      <data key="d0">FAN SUPPLY (FRONT) &amp; EXHAUST (REAR)</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Mechanical ventilation configuration that supplies air at the front and exhausts at the rear to create a front-to-rear airflow path intended to transport and remove airborne contaminants in a stationary bus.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="FAN SUPPLY (FRONT) &amp; SUPPLY (REAR)">
      <data key="d0">FAN SUPPLY (FRONT) &amp; SUPPLY (REAR)</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">Mechanical ventilation configuration with supply fans at both the front and rear of the stationary bus, promoting mixing without a dedicated exhaust path; included in normalized exposure comparisons.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="P_CO2 (NORMALIZED INHALATION OF CO2)">
      <data key="d0">P_CO2 (NORMALIZED INHALATION OF CO2)</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">A dimensionless metric defined as inhalation volume of CO2 relative to the volume emitted at specified release positions (indicated by arrows), used to quantify transport and exposure in bus tests.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="P_PARTICLES (NORMALIZED PARTICLE EXPOSURE)">
      <data key="d0">P_PARTICLES (NORMALIZED PARTICLE EXPOSURE)</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">A dimensionless metric representing normalized particle exposure at bus measurement positions, used alongside P_CO2 to examine coupling between rebreathed tracer gas and particulates.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NORMALIZED EXPOSURE (P) IN BUS">
      <data key="d0">NORMALIZED EXPOSURE (P) IN BUS</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">A dimensionless normalized exposure metric reported across configurations in a stationary city bus, enabling comparison of inhaled tracer exposure under differing ventilation states.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INHALATION VOLUME OF CO2 IN MOVING TESTS WITH MANNEQUINS">
      <data key="d0">INHALATION VOLUME OF CO2 IN MOVING TESTS WITH MANNEQUINS</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">Figure 7: Measurements of inhalation volume of CO2 relative to emitted volume at specified positions in a moving bus with mannequins, characterizing motion-induced airflow and exposure patterns.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.65</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="RELATIONSHIPS BETWEEN P CO2 AND P PARTICLES IN THE BUS">
      <data key="d0">RELATIONSHIPS BETWEEN P CO2 AND P PARTICLES IN THE BUS</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">Figure 8: Analysis of relationships between P_CO2 and P_PARTICLES at five measurement positions with AC on versus off, assessing how AC operation modulates coupling between rebreathed tracer gas and particulate exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NORMALIZED EXPOSURE DATA IN THE STATIONARY CITY BUS">
      <data key="d0">NORMALIZED EXPOSURE DATA IN THE STATIONARY CITY BUS</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">Figure 9: Dataset comparing normalized exposure under four configurations: (A) windows closed, AC off, fan off; (B) windows open, AC off, fan off; (C) windows closed, AC off, front supply &amp; rear exhaust; (D) windows closed, AC off, front supply &amp; rear supply.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INFLUENCE OF NATURAL VENTILATION DESIGN ON THE DISPERSION OF PATHOGEN-LADEN DROPLETS IN A COACH BUS.">
      <data key="d0">INFLUENCE OF NATURAL VENTILATION DESIGN ON THE DISPERSION OF PATHOGEN-LADEN DROPLETS IN A COACH BUS.</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">Luo et al., Sci Total Environ (2023): Assesses how natural ventilation design affects dispersion of pathogen-laden droplets in a coach bus, providing external corroboration for window-opening strategies in buses.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.6</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_5</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NATURAL VENTILATION STRATEGY">
      <data key="d0">NATURAL VENTILATION STRATEGY</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">An engineering control using wind and buoyancy-driven airflows (e.g., opening windows and doors) to increase outdoor air exchange, diluting and removing infectious aerosols in occupied spaces.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.88</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="DIFFERENT VENTILATION STRATEGIES">
      <data key="d0">DIFFERENT VENTILATION STRATEGIES</data>
      <data key="d1">ENGINEERING_CONTROL</data>
      <data key="d2">A set of alternative ventilation approaches (e.g., varying air exchange, supply/exhaust configurations) that change airflow and dilution, assessed for effects on indoor contaminant dynamics in confined spaces.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.8</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="HOSPITAL LIFT">
      <data key="d0">HOSPITAL LIFT</data>
      <data key="d1">HOSPITAL_ZONE</data>
      <data key="d2">An elevator within a hospital, a small, enclosed, and frequently occupied zone where aerosol accumulation and short-range dispersion are critical for infection control.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.75</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_6,e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_7</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="INDOOR CO2 CONCENTRATION">
      <data key="d0">INDOOR CO2 CONCENTRATION</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">Carbon dioxide levels used as a proxy for rebreathed air fraction and ventilation effectiveness; lower concentrations generally indicate better dilution in occupied spaces.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.72</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="COUGH DROPLET DISPERSION">
      <data key="d0">COUGH DROPLET DISPERSION</data>
      <data key="d1">EFFECTIVENESS_MEASURE</data>
      <data key="d2">Spatial and temporal spread of cough-generated droplets/aerosols in indoor air, used to evaluate how ventilation strategies influence near-field and room-scale exposure.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.7</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="NATURAL VENTILATION STRATEGY AND RELATED ISSUES TO PREVENT CORONAVIRUS DISEASE 2019 (COVID-19) AIRBORNE TRANSMISSION IN A SCHOOL BUILDING.">
      <data key="d0">NATURAL VENTILATION STRATEGY AND RELATED ISSUES TO PREVENT CORONAVIRUS DISEASE 2019 (COVID-19) AIRBORNE TRANSMISSION IN A SCHOOL BUILDING.</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">Park et al., 2021 (Sci Total Environ) study examining application and practical considerations of natural ventilation in a school setting for mitigating COVID-19 airborne transmission.</data>
      <data key="d3">0.74</data>
      <data key="d4">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee_chunk_6</data>
      <data key="d5">e45568c3-e22e-4830-92f5-64de955e8aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="[VENTILATION CONCEPTS IN SCHOOLS FOR THE PREVENTION OF TRANSMISSION OF HIGHLY INFECTIOUS VIRUSES (SARS-COV-2) BY AEROSOLS IN INDOOR AIR].">
      <data key="d0">[VENTILATION CONCEPTS IN SCHOOLS FOR THE PREVENTION OF TRANSMISSION OF HIGHLY INFECTIOUS VIRUSES (SARS-COV-2) BY AEROSOLS IN INDOOR AIR].</data>
      <data key="d1">VALIDATION_STUDY</data>
      <data key="d2">Birmili et al., 2021 review outlining ventilation approaches in schools aimed at preventing aerosol transmission of highly infectious viruses, including SARS-CoV-2.</data>
